 adaptations to the same world-wide development. These are the kinds of concerns the interdisciplinary group of scholars addresses in this volume. Contributors include Moshe Amon ("Utopias and Counter-Utopias"), Alan Davies ("The Rise o Racism in the Nineteenth Century: Symptom of Modernity"), Robert Ellwood, Jr. ("Modern Religion as Folk Religion"), Irving Hexham ("Modernity or Reaction in South Africa: The Case of Afrikaner Religion"), Shotaro Iida ("Japanese New Religions"), Shelia McDonough ("modernity in Islamic Persepctive"), William Nicholls ("Immanent Transcendence: Spirituality in a Scientific and Critical Age"), K. Dad Prithipaul ("Modernity and Religious Studies"), Tom Sinclair-Faulkner ("Caution: Moralists at Work"), Huston Smith ("Can Modernity Accommodate Transcendence?"), and John Wilson ("Modernity and Religion: A Problem of Perspective").  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPensée religieusexCongrèsx20e siècle. 0aReligionvCongresses. 0aReligionxCongresses. 0aReligionxCongrès. 0aReligion. 0aReligious thoughtxCongressesx20th century. 0aReligious thoughty20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligious thought. 0aSecularismvCongresses. 0aSecularismxCongresses. 0aSécularismexCongrès. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAmon, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Alan T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllwood, Jr., Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHexham, Irving, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonough, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicholls, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicholls, William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc